<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920205-0017</DOCNO><DOCID>920205-0017.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- General Dynamics Corp.:   Plan to Stop Building Sub   To Cost Up to 4,000 Jobs</HL><DATE>02/05/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   GD LABOR</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)STOCK AND BOND RATINGS (RTG)</IN><NS>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)BOND andamp; STOCK RATINGS (RTG)</NS><GV>DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><RE>CONNECTICUT (CT)MISSOURI (MO)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   General Dynamics Corp. said President Bush's proposed haltof the Seawolf submarine program will lead to the eliminationof as many as 4,000 jobs, or 19% of the work force at itsElectric Boat division.   The big defense contractor previously had said the Seawolfdecision would have &quot;major implications&quot; for the division,but hadn't estimated work force reductions.</LP><TEXT>   Some of the 21,000 employees at the division based inGroton, Conn., will begin receiving layoff notices Feb. 18,the Falls Church, Va., company said. General Dynamics, whichhas a total work force of 80,000, had been scheduled to buildtwo more of the submarines after the one now being completed.   Even if the two additional submarines were included in thedefense budget, the company's work force would still be cutby more than 2,000, General Dynamics said.   Separately, Standard andamp; Poor's Corp. said it placed theratings of General Dynamic's commercial paper and senior andsubordinated debt on its CreditWatch list with positiveimplications, reflecting company plans to reduce debt to moreconservative levels.</TEXT></DOC>